      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for NIH quantity of interest is less than 5% on the medium mesh used for production runs, verified by three-mesh Richardson extrapolation.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse 4.2 M cells, medium 9.8 M cells, fine 22.1 M cells) was conducted at the 3 L/min, 3000 RPM operating point. GCI for NIH was 3.7% between medium and fine meshes. The medium mesh was selected for all production runs. Spatial order of accuracy p=1.94 consistent with second-order discretisation scheme."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions for validation activities are documented with inlet flow rate uncertainty ≤2% and rotational speed uncertainty ≤0.5%, traceable to NIST-calibrated instruments.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro test conditions were documented in test protocol TP-2024-CPB-003. Coriolis flow meter uncertainty ±1.1%; tachometer uncertainty ±0.3%. Blood analogue fluid (glycerol-water 36% w/w) viscosity measured at 37°C with cone-plate rheometer, uncertainty ±2.5%. All instruments NIST-traceable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (mean absolute error or NRMSE) computed between CFD-predicted NIH and experimental NIH across all validation operating points; metric must be below pre-specified threshold of 15%.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed for both the primary (internal, NIH index) and secondary (Fraser 2012, NIH index) validation activities. Primary MAE=8.3%; secondary NRMSE=6.1%, R²=0.94. Both metrics satisfy the pre-specified acceptance thresholds. The assessment team regarded the secondary comparison against Fraser 2012 as providing independent corroboration of model form validity across a wide operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation QoI (NIH index derived from power-law hemolysis model integrated along Lagrangian particle tracks) is the same scalar quantity used to evaluate the COU acceptance criterion (RH < 1).",
      "rationale": "The NIH index is the direct precursor to the relative hemolysis index RH used in the COU acceptance criterion. Lagrangian particle tracking with the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model was used consistently in both validation and production simulations. No transformation or surrogate mapping is required between the validation QoI and the decision QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities cover the pump geometry, fluid properties, and at least three of the five COU operating points; any gap in operating-point coverage is addressed by interpolation uncertainty analysis.",
      "rationale": "The primary validation activity used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at CPB-range operating conditions (2–5 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM), directly overlapping the COU envelope. The secondary validation activity (Fraser 2012) used the same pump geometry at VAD-range conditions (3–8 L/min, 2500–4500 RPM); the assessment team noted that the overlapping flow-rate range (3–5 L/min) and identical geometry provide supporting evidence of model validity. The positive agreement observed in both activities was taken collectively as sufficient validation evidence for MRL 2."
    },
    {
