      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; default Gradation 1 accepted.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, explicit iterative convergence error quantification beyond residual monitoring is not required. Residuals converged to 1×10⁻⁵ for all equations; mass imbalance <0.01%. Factor scoped out per MRL 2 requirements table."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2; analyst qualification records reviewed.",
      "rationale": "All CFD analysts hold documented training records for ANSYS Fluent and have completed the institutional CFD-for-medical-devices competency assessment. Formal use-error quantification is not required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence closure (SST k-ω) and hemolysis constitutive model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger power law) are justified by literature precedent for centrifugal blood pump CFD at the Reynolds numbers present in the COU.",
      "rationale": "SST k-ω turbulence closure is widely used and validated for internal rotating-machinery flows at Re 10³–10⁵. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is the de facto standard for regulatory CFD submissions for blood-contacting devices. Model form uncertainty was assessed as low relative to the 15% acceptance band."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Inlet velocity profiles, fluid viscosity, and rotational speed are specified with uncertainties; a one-at-a-time sensitivity study confirms that NIH is most sensitive to rotational speed (±8% NIH per ±100 RPM) and least sensitive to viscosity (±1.2% NIH per ±5% viscosity).",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions were derived from clinical CPB flow specifications (ISO 7199:2016) and pump manufacturer data sheets. One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis over ±5% perturbations in all primary inputs was completed. Rotational speed is the dominant input uncertainty driver; its uncertainty contribution (±8% NIH) is within the acceptance band when combined with discretisation error (3.7% GCI)."
    },
